net.zerobandwidth.android.lib.database.sqlitehouse.refractor

Class SQLDateLens

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.zerobandwidth.android.lib.database.sqlitehouse.refractor.Lens<java.sql.Date>
      • net.zerobandwidth.android.lib.database.sqlitehouse.refractor.SQLDateLens
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Refractor<java.sql.Date>

    public class SQLDateLens
extends Lens<java.sql.Date>
implements Refractor<java.sql.Date>
    Marshals Date objects. The lens converts all dates into integer GMT timestamps for storage in the DB, then recreates the Date objects upon retrieval. This is because integer timestamps are more reliably stored and are absolute (no fretting about timezones).
    Since:
    zerobandwidth-net/android 0.1.4 (#26)

      • getSQLiteDefaultValue

        public java.sql.Date getSQLiteDefaultValue()
        Defines the default value of a date column as null. This is different from most Java datetime-related objects, which initialize by default to the current time. In a database, this should instead be left as null, to be overwritten with an explicit time later.
